[2] Brazil (Espirito Santo)
Date: Tue 16 Jun 2009
Source: A Gazeta Online [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://gazetaonline.globo.com/_conteudo/2009/06/100562-espirito+santo+tem+228+notificacoes+de+dengue+por+dia+em+2009.html>


Espirito Santo has 288 reported dengue cases per day in 2009
------------------------------------------------------------
According to the data from the Environmental Surveillance Nucleus of
the state Secretariat of Health (SESA), Espirito Santo has registered
43 536 reported cases of dengue since the beginning of the year
[2009] up to 1 Jun [2009]. Given that the period covers 151
consecutive days, there have been about 288 dengue cases reported per
day in the state. The municipalities with the greatest number of
cases reported are, in order, Serra, Vila Velha, Vitoria, Nova
Venecia, and Cariacica.

As of Friday, 12 [Jun 2009], there have been 1490 suspected serious
dengue cases registered that have recovered. Of these, 278 were
confirmed as dengue with complications, 138 as DHF, and 22 were
negative and discarded as dengue [cases]. The other [cases] are under
investigation.

in 2009 there have been 33 [dengue] deaths confirmed by SESA and 21
are under investigation by the Secretariat Committee to Investigate
Deaths. Of these 33 deaths, 17 were due to DHF and registered in the
municipalities of Serra, Linhares, Colatina, Vila Velha, Guarapari,
Nova Venecia, Conceicao da Barra, and Vitoria. The other 16 deaths,
classified as dengue with complications, occurred in Vila Velha,
Cariacica, Baixo Guandu, Nova Venecia, Vitoria, and Serra.

Dengue with complications is any case that does not fit the criteria
for classification as DHF and the diagnosis of classical dengue is
unsatisfactory given the severity of the clinical and laboratory
picture. In this situation, any one of the signs that are
characteristic of symptoms [atypical for dengue] include neurological
disorders, cardiopulmonary dysfunction, liver failure, and
gastrointestinal bleeding, for example. The analyses of cases under
investigation are completed within 90 days, starting at the date of
death.

--
